<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1897-04-23T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1897-04-23T00:00:00-05:00" n="197" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d197">
                        <head><hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Sherman</persName> to Mr.
                                    <persName type="to">Uhl</persName></hi>.</head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1897-04-23"><hi rend="italic">April 23,
                                1897</hi></date>.</dateline>
                            <seg rendition="#left">No. 372.]</seg></opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have to inform you that your dispatch
                            No. 307, of March 29 last, in regard to the treatment of naturalized
                            American citizens of German origin, upon their return to their native
                            country on business or pleasure, has been received.</p>
                        <p>The Department fully approves your note of March 29, 1897, to the German
                            foreign office on the subject in question.</p>
                        <p>Respectfully, yours,</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">John Sherman.</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>